<Learn
  title="Cold Email Rules & Compliance | Warmbly"
  description="CAN-SPAM, GDPR, CASL, PECR. what each actually says, and how to send cold mail compliantly without hiring a lawyer."
  reading="10 min read"
  updated="2026-05-02"
>
  <h2>Why this matters</h2>
  <p>
    Cold email is not illegal in most jurisdictions, but the rules around it vary. Getting them wrong invites both fines and the worse outcome: spam complaints that damage your sender reputation across the entire contact list.
  </p>
  <p>
    This guide is general information, not legal advice. If you're sending at scale to regulated jurisdictions, run your specific approach past counsel.
  </p>

  <h2>United States. CAN-SPAM (2003)</h2>
  <p>
    CAN-SPAM applies to "commercial electronic mail messages". It does <em>not</em> require prior consent for cold B2B email. It does require:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Truthful "From" and routing information.</li>
    <li>Subject lines that aren't misleading.</li>
    <li>Identification as an advertisement (interpreted loosely for B2B context).</li>
    <li>A valid physical postal address.</li>
    <li>A clear unsubscribe mechanism honoured within 10 business days.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    For Warmbly's defaults, this means: include a physical address in your sender profile, never spoof a name or domain, and ensure unsubscribe replies are auto-suppressed.
  </p>

  <h2>European Union and UK. GDPR + PECR</h2>
  <p>
    GDPR applies to personal data of EU/UK residents. PECR (in the UK) and ePrivacy directives in EU member states specifically cover electronic marketing.
  </p>

  <h3>B2B cold mail</h3>
  <p>
    Cold mail to <strong>corporate</strong> recipients (a named role at a company) is generally permitted under "legitimate interest" if:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>The recipient has a clear business reason to receive the message (relevance test).</li>
    <li>You can demonstrate you've considered their rights and interests (balancing test).</li>
    <li>You provide a clear opt-out mechanism.</li>
    <li>You honour opt-outs immediately.</li>
    <li>You can tell them, on request, where you obtained their contact details.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>B2C marketing mail</h3>
  <p>
    Generally requires prior consent. Cold marketing to consumer addresses in the EU/UK is risky without it.
  </p>

  <h3>Data processing record</h3>
  <p>
    Keep a record of where you sourced each contact and the legitimate interest you relied on. Warmbly's contact import wizard captures source and import notes for exactly this.
  </p>

  <h2>Canada. CASL (2014)</h2>
  <p>
    CASL is the strictest of the major regimes. It requires <em>express or implied consent</em> before sending commercial electronic messages to Canadian recipients.
  </p>
  <p>
    Implied consent exists where the recipient has a relevant existing business relationship, conspicuously published their business email without an explicit "no marketing" statement, or asked for information from your business in the last 6 months.
  </p>
  <p>
    Every message must include sender identification, contact info, and a working unsubscribe. Penalties for non-compliance can reach CAD $10M per violation for organisations.
  </p>

  <h2>Australia. Spam Act 2003</h2>
  <p>
    Requires consent (express, inferred or implied), accurate sender identification and a functional unsubscribe. Inferred consent is generous for B2B but not consumer marketing.
  </p>

  <h2>Practical cold-mail compliance checklist</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Use a real From: name and a domain you actually own.</li>
    <li>Include a physical mailing address in your sender profile / footer.</li>
    <li>Provide a clear opt-out. "Reply STOP to opt out" or a one-click link.</li>
    <li>Auto-suppress recipients who opt out, across all future sequences and campaigns.</li>
    <li>Record where each contact was sourced and your basis for contacting them.</li>
    <li>Only contact role accounts and named business addresses for B2B; avoid personal addresses unless you have explicit consent.</li>
    <li>Customise the message for relevance. boilerplate to thousands of strangers is the loudest possible compliance and reputation risk.</li>
    <li>Skip Canadian and EU consumer-mail recipients unless you have documented consent.</li>
    <li>Honour opt-outs within 24 hours, not the legal maximum.</li>
    <li>If you operate a privacy policy, link to it from your footer.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>How Warmbly helps</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Sender profiles include physical address fields that render in every send.</li>
    <li>Opt-out detection on incoming replies (STOP, unsubscribe, "please remove me").</li>
